      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/software-quality-assurance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "SQA Gradation 2 compliance",
        "description": "Commercial CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2023 R1) with documented release notes and regression test suite. Version control applied to all case files and user-defined functions. Achieves Gradation 2: solver is commercially validated and version-controlled case files are archived with checksums."
      },
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2023 R1 is a commercially released solver subject to the vendor's internal SQA program. All simulation input decks, UDFs implementing the Giersiepen hemolysis power-law model, and post-processing scripts are stored in a Git repository with tagged releases. Gradation 2 is required and achieved at MRL 2 for a Class II device."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/numerical-code-verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/numerical-code-verification",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Code verification via benchmark test cases",
        "description": "Solver passes FDA benchmark nozzle and backward-facing step test cases with L2 norm residuals below 1e-5. Achieves Gradation 2: published benchmark comparisons confirm correct numerical implementation of governing equations."
      },
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent has been verified against the FDA benchmark nozzle (Hariharan et al. 2011) and the lid-driven cavity benchmark. Residual convergence to 1e-6 was confirmed for all operating points. Published verification studies for this solver on hemodynamic applications are cited in the evidence package."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/discretization-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/discretization-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "GCI < 5% on hemolysis index QoI",
        "description": "Grid Convergence Index (GCI) computed per Celik et al. (2008) on three systematically refined meshes (4.2M, 9.8M, 21.6M cells). GCI on the normalized hemolysis index must be below 5%. Achieved GCI of 2.1%, exceeding Gradation 2 and meeting Gradation 3."
      },
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was performed with refinement ratio r = 1.33. The observed order of convergence p = 1.94 is consistent with second-order spatial discretization. GCI_fine = 2.1% on the hemolysis index QoI, well below the 5% threshold. Richardson extrapolation confirmed asymptotic convergence. Achieved level 3 exceeds required level 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/test-conditions",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Experimental boundary conditions reproduced within ±5%",
        "description": "Inlet flow rates (2–6 L/min), rotational speeds (1500–3500 RPM), and fluid properties (bovine blood analogue, viscosity 3.5 mPa·s at 37°C) match FDA GCBP experimental protocol within ±5% measurement uncertainty. Gradation 2 achieved."
      },
      "rationale": "CFD boundary conditions were set to match the five operating points in the FDA GCBP experimental dataset. Inlet velocity profiles derived from Womersley flow theory at Re = 250–850. Fluid properties use the Newtonian approximation validated for shear rates > 100 s-1 predominant in the pump. Temperature maintained at 37°C ± 0.5°C per experimental protocol."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/output-comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Normalized hemolysis index within experimental uncertainty band",
        "description": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) must fall within the 95% confidence interval of experimental NIH measurements across all 5 operating points. Mean absolute percentage error (MAPE) must be below 15%. Achieved MAPE of 9.3%."
      },
      "rationale": "CFD-predicted NIH values were compared against experimental measurements from the FDA GCBP study. At all five operating points the predictions lie within the experimental 95% CI (bootstrap, n=6 replicates). MAPE = 9.3% across operating points, below the 15% acceptance threshold. Worst-case point (5 L/min, 3500 RPM) shows 12.1% deviation, still within CI."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/relevance-qoi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/relevance-qoi",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI directly maps to regulatory hemolysis endpoint",
        "description": "The primary QoI (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH, and relative hemolysis index, RH) must be directly traceable to the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1 vs. predicate device) specified in FDA guidance. Gradation 2: QoI is the same metric used in the regulatory submission."
      },
      "rationale": "The hemolysis QoIs (NIH and RH) are the metrics specified in ASTM F1841 and referenced in FDA guidance for blood-contacting device submissions. The relative hemolysis index RH < 1 is the direct regulatory acceptance criterion. There is no translation or surrogate relationship between the modeled QoI and the regulatory endpoint."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/relevance-validation-activities",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/relevance-validation-activities",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation geometry and operating conditions span COU envelope",
        "description": "Validation activities must use the same pump geometry family and operating envelope (flow rate 2–6 L/min, speed 1500–3500 RPM) as the COU. At least 4 of 5 operating points must be covered. Gradation 2 achieved with all 5 points covered using the FDA GCBP geometry."
      },
      "rationale": "Validation was performed on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry, which is the same geometric family as the device under assessment. All five COU operating points are covered by the validation dataset. Fluid properties, rotational boundary conditions, and hemolysis model parameters are identical between validation and COU simulations."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/numerical-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error as a distinct credibility factor addresses iterative convergence errors arising from algebraic multigrid or iterative linear solvers in implicit time-stepping schemes. In this steady-state MRF simulation, all residuals converge monotonically to below 1e-6 (continuity, momentum, k, omega) with no evidence of iterative divergence or cycling. The solver error contribution to the hemolysis QoI is bounded by the GCI analysis already captured under the Discretization Error factor, and no separate iterative-solver error budget is required at MRL 2 for a Class II device with a converged steady-state solution. This factor is therefore not applicable to the current COU."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Use error as a credibility factor pertains to errors introduced by end-user misapplication of the simulation tool in a production clinical or operational context — for example, a clinician entering incorrect patient-specific parameters into a deployed decision-support system. In this assessment the CFD model is operated exclusively by trained simulation engineers within a controlled R&D environment and is not deployed as a clinical decision-support tool accessible to non-expert users. The COU explicitly scopes model influence as MEDIUM with confirmatory bench testing, and there is no pathway by which end-user interaction with the model could introduce errors into the hemolysis prediction. This factor is therefore not applicable to the current COU."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty (turbulence model selection, hemolysis constitutive law) is not required to be formally assessed at MRL 2 for a Class II device under ASME V&V 40-2018. The SST k-omega turbulence model and Giersiepen power-law hemolysis model are standard choices for centrifugal blood pump CFD with documented use in the literature. Formal model form assessment is deferred to MRL 3 activities if the device advances to a higher-risk classification."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "rationale": "Formal uncertainty quantification of model inputs (material properties, geometric tolerances, boundary condition distributions) is not required at MRL 2 for a Class II device. Nominal input values are traceable to ASTM F1841 and the FDA GCBP experimental protocol. Sensitivity of outputs to input variation is partially addressed through the five-operating-point sweep. Full probabilistic input uncertainty propagation is deferred to higher MRL activities."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "rationale": "Statistical characterization of test sample variability (pump-to-pump geometric variation, blood analogue batch effects) is not required at MRL 2 for a Class II device. The FDA GCBP experimental data used for validation was collected on a single reference geometry pump. Sample-to-sample variability assessment is deferred to higher MRL activities or design verification testing."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/equivalency-input-parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "rationale": "Formal equivalency analysis of input parameters between the validation context and the COU (e.g., blood rheology differences between bovine analogue and human blood, patient population variability in hematocrit) is not required at MRL 2 for a Class II device. The Newtonian fluid approximation is consistent between validation and COU simulations. Full equivalency mapping is deferred to MRL 3 activities."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/cou1-cpb-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/morrison/org/fda-cdrh-computational-modeling",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (CPB hemolysis worst-case identification, Class II, MRL 2) is accepted based on the following structured evidence: (1) Seven factors were formally assessed, all achieving their required Gradation 2 levels or above. Discretization error achieved Gradation 3 (GCI = 2.1%), exceeding the MRL 2 requirement. Output comparison demonstrated MAPE = 9.3% across all five operating points, within the 15% acceptance threshold and within experimental 95% CIs. (2) Two factors (Numerical Solver Error, Use Error) are marked not-applicable with documented rationale: solver error is subsumed by the GCI-bounded discretization error analysis in a converged steady-state simulation, and use error does not apply because the model is operated exclusively by trained engineers in a controlled R&D environment with no clinical end-user pathway. (3) Four factors (Model Form, Model Inputs, Test Samples, Equivalency of Input Parameters) are not-assessed, consistent with ASME V&V 40-2018 requirements at MRL 2 for a Class II device. (4) All validation results carry comparedAgainst, wasGeneratedBy, and hasUncertaintyQuantification links providing a complete provenance chain to foundational experimental evidence. (5) No factor has achievedLevel below requiredLevel; no offset rationale is required. The model is fit for its intended use of identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for regulatory submission.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
